item.l: Mr Fox addressing his friends from the Kings Arms tavern Feby 14, 1784
(For description see other impression). c.February 1784 Etching
Hawkins, Edward to The British Museum
Mr Fox addressing his friends from the Kings Arms tavern Feby 14, 1784

Headed by frontispiece, showing that it is taken from one of the many pamphlets issued in connexion with the struggle between Pitt and Fox. Another representation of the scene in Palace Yard, see BMSat 6421, &c. The faade of the tavern fills the greater part of the design, showing a central bow, surmounted by the royal arms, and four stories with sash-windows, all blank, except for the head and shoulders of Fox, larger than life, addressing a crowd beneath. In the foreground are full-length figures looking up at Fox. They include Sam House (right) in his accustomed dress, Jeffery Dunstan, with his bag over his shoulder, a lamplighter with an oil- I can and a long ladder; a carter in a ragged coat holding a whip; a sweep with soot-bag and brushes; a mechanic wearing an apron; a butcher with a club; and a man with a box slung round his shoulders, who may be a rat-catcher. Between these men and the railings of the tavern is a dense crowd indicated by a sea of heads. 14 February 1784 Etching
Banks, Dorothea to The British Museum
A knight of the back stairs with his three best friends

Wray stands holding in front of him a large guinea, representing his coat of arms; the supporters are, dexter, the Devil (left) and, sinister, a figure dressed as Folly who represents Jackson, steward to the Duke of Newcastle and one of Wray's election committee. Wray holds a ladder, emblem of the back stairs, see BMSat 6417, &c.; in his right hand, which rests on the guinea, is a conspirator's dark lantern. 'Judas' is inscribed across his hat in large letters. He says: "Talk not to me of Ghosts me thought I saw T....rs Ghost, who haunts my Guilty conscience" (probably Sir Charles Turner, d. 1783, one of the most respected of the Rockingham Whigs). On the monstrous guinea are the royal arms reversed and burlesqued: the leopards resemble monkeys, the lion has a barbed tail. Round the edge is inscribed 'The Golden Key or Secret Influence'. The Devil, nude with horns, hoofs, and barbed tail, is kneeling; he says, "Judas my child be not fearfull of Your election you are certain of my Vote, tho but a Lodger Lord." (Lord Mountmorres, one of the most determined enemies of Fox, was asserted in a Foxite handbill of 16 Apr. to be a lodger in a hotel, not a householder. 'Westminster Election', p. 106; Wraxall, 'Memoirs', 1884, iii. 297.) Jackson (half-length) has satyr's ears and a barrel in place of a hat; he is dressed as a zany or pierrot, in his right hand is a rattle. Across his back is inscribed: 'The Scrub & Beer Butler to the Duke of N--c--stle & Public Fool to Judas Iscari[ot]'. Beneath the design is etched: 'From such evils Good Lord Deliver us'. 2 April 1784 Etching, partly hand-coloured
Banks, Dorothea to The British Museum
Sir Zealous Godfrey giving a bouillon raffraichissant, to his friends
(For description see other impression). 7 April 1784 Etching
Hawkins, Edward to The British Museum
La Tour d'Auvergne, Godefroy Charles Henri de
Sir Zealous Godfrey giving a bouillon raffraichissant, to his friends
(For description see other impression). 7 April 1784 Etching
Banks, Dorothea to The British Museum
La Tour d'Auvergne, Godefroy Charles Henri de
Sir Zealous Godfrey giving a bouillon raffraichissant, to his friends

North and Fox as invalids sit (left) close together in arm-chairs, both wearing dressing-gowns, instead of coats, and night-caps. A man approaches them from the right holding in each hand a bowl of soup in which are frogs; one frog falls to the ground, two others sit on the floor. He holds his hat under his arm; he has a chain of alternate wine-bottles and glasses across his shoulder in place of a ribbon and, in place of a star, a medallion inscribed 'Never Tired' on which is a gridiron (the emblem of the Beef Steak Club); he wears a sword. Fox and North have expressions of melancholy discomfort; Fox places a hand on his chest saying, "Oh ... Oh ... Oh I shall never get my Strength again"; North says, "will this Bouillon give me a new Majority in the house". The man with the soup, whose French nationality is indicated by the frogs but not by his appearance or dress, says, "yes Yes my dear Friends it will mend your Constitutions Apace." 7 April 1784 Hand-coloured etching
Banks, Dorothea to The British Museum
La Tour d'Auvergne, Godefroy Charles Henri de

Three ladies stand together, the centre one full-face, the others facing each other in profile. All wear the bosoms then fashionable, the covering gauze of these extends from back over the shoulders. They also wear the inflated 'derriere', see BMSat 6874, which completed the absurd silhouette of the day. Two hold huge muffs, the third (right) folds her arms under her bosom. All have the much puffed-out coiffure then fashionable, making the features look very small; that of the centre lady is composed of minute curls, that of the others is smooth with tresses hanging on the shoulders. 28 May 1786 Hand-coloured etching
Smith, William to The British Museum
A Perry-lous situation; or, the doctor and his friends keeping the bumbrusher and her myrmidons at bay.

Two opposing groups confront each other: on the left is a constable with a staff, a timorous assistant, and on the extreme left a schoolmistress holding up a birch-rod. They are threatened by a tall young man, who puts his arm round the waist of a young woman, and by another man; both aim pistols at the constable. An older woman, on the extreme right, stands protectingly behind the young woman. The schoolmistress says, "Let me get her again into my hands and I'll tickle her Toby nicely - Consider my Reward, Gentlemen, I'll now give two hundred pounds." The constable's assistant says, "Ay, Mistress, but we mun consider our own sens also - he is a desperate looking dog". The constable, whose red waistcoat suggests the Bow Street runner, says, "In the name of Mistress Sharp-look-out, the Schoolmistress, I command you to deliver up little Miss - and return to the pestle and Mortar". Perry, who has eloped with the girl, answers, "Throw Physic to the dogs, I'll none of it!" She says to him, "Dear Doctor save me from my governess." Perry's supporter says, "No farther at your peril." The woman says, "Dont be alarm'd, Miss there is no danger." 17 April 1791 Hand-coloured etching
Hawkins, Edward to The British Museum
Old friends with new faces, or welcome visitors to John Bull.

John Bull (right), knife in hand, looks delightedly at a ladder that slants across the left part of the design. On this are a large loaf, and, on a higher rung, a foaming tankard. The former says: "I am coming down Johnny"; the latter adds: "So am I too." John says: "Are you my Lads - then D------n me I'll have at you." c. October 1801 Etching
Hawkins, Edward to The British Museum
John Bull and his friends welcoming home the definitive treaty!

John Bull, a 'cit', hat in hand, bows to a young woman (right) who curtsies slightly, holding out a paper, 'Definitive Treaty', and an olive twig. Behind him is an immense joint of beef supported on human legs, politely bowing; in it are stuck a knife and fork and sprigs of olive and holly. Other objects follow closely. John says: "I've taken the liberty, Madam, of bringing down to the coast a few of my most esteem'd Friends to welcome your arrival. We'll stick up our houses with holly, We'll broach a tub of hummingbub And have no more of the rub-a-dub-dud Dear Madam, we'll all be jolly!" She answers: "You are very obliging, Mr Bull, I have been detain'd a long time on the other side of the water, but you remember old adage, Better late than never." On the extreme left are a large loaf inscribed 'Best Wheaten Flour', a piece of bacon saying, "Make way, there, for Mr Gammon of Bacon", and part of a cheese saying, "I hope you are well, Miss Butter". A cylinder of butter, supported by legs in a petticoat, answers: "Pretty well I thank you, Mr Cheese, don't you think the weather melting hot?" A frothing tankard of Brown Stout, ornamented with the Royal Arms, as in BMSat 9850, stands on top-booted legs. c. April 1802 Etching
